whereas.text:
Whereas the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear
			 Weapons (NPT) (21 UST 483) entered into force and became part of United States
			 law on March 5, 1970;

Whereas more countries (a total of 188) have ratified the
			 NPT than any other arms limitation and disarmament agreement, a testament to
			 the significance of the NPT;

Whereas the long-term viability of the nonproliferation
			 goal is at risk if the United States fails to implement its article VI
			 obligations;

paragraph.text:
“the threat or use of nuclear weapons would
			 generally be considered contrary to the rules of international law applicable
			 in armed conflict”;

whereas.text:
Whereas the SORT called for a decrease in the number of
			 deployed strategic nuclear warheads, but projected storage of thousands of
			 strategic warheads, including many capable of quick redeployment;

paragraph.text:
reiterated
			 Administration plans not to support ratification of the Comprehensive Test Ban
			 Treaty;

contrary to
			 fundamental requirements of international law, because the United Nations
			 Charter does not permit preventive war;

immoral, because
			 they place a threat of mass destruction, and the assertion of a right to
			 initiate war, at the core of United States foreign policy;

subparagraph.text:
implementation and
			 observance of article VI of the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear
			 Weapons (NPT) (21 UST 483);

begin verifiable
			 and irreversible reductions in the United States strategic and tactical nuclear
			 weapons and their delivery systems;

cooperate with the
			 Russian Federation to remove from deployment nuclear weapons that presently are
			 operational and ready to be launched on short notice;

reaffirm the
			 moratorium on nuclear testing and work for ratification of the Comprehensive
			 Test Ban Treaty at the earliest possible date;

terminate the
			 declared United States policy of preventive warfare as a response to threats
			 from weapons of mass destruction (WMD);

obtain the
			 approval of the Senate or the entire Congress as a condition for withdrawal
			 from and termination of both existing and future security treaties;
